docs.abstract: The president spent Sunday out of sight, berating opponents on Twitter, even as some of his campaign advisers were recommending that he deliver a televised address to an anxious nation.
docs.snippet: The president spent Sunday out of sight, berating opponents on Twitter, even as some of his campaign advisers were recommending that he deliver a televised address to an anxious nation.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Inside the White House, the mood was bristling with tension. Hundreds of protesters were gathering outside the gates, shouting curses at President Trump and in some cases throwing bricks and bottles. Nervous for his safety, Secret Service agents abruptly rushed the president to the underground bunker used in the past during terrorist attacks.

headline.main: As Protests and Violence Spill Over, Trump Shrinks Back
headline.print_headline: Trump Offers No Calming Words As Tumult Reaches White House

docs.lead_paragraph: Students at a New Jersey high school logged into their remote landscape and design class on Wednesday morning expecting their teacher to lead a discussion about climate change. docs.abstract: A level internet playing field lets them, and everyone else, bypass powerful gatekeepers.
docs.snippet: A level internet playing field lets them, and everyone else, bypass powerful gatekeepers.
docs.lead_paragraph: Somewhere at a comedy club, a new comedian is about to hit the stage for the first time. She will bring with her the modern tool of the trade: her cellphone, equipped with the notes she has typed, a recording app, and five minutes of material that isn’t worth all that technology. This set is going to bomb. Hard. But she will repeat this process — night in, night out, until over time, that five-minute performance becomes tighter and more polished. Eventually, she’ll ask a friend to use a phone to record a set. And that night she will kill. Utterly destroy the room. That will be the first time she uploads footage of herself performing to the internet. Her life will never be the same.

headline.main: Net Neutrality: Why Artists and Activists Can’t Afford to Lose It

docs.lead_paragraph: The rapper Tupac Shakur once broke down the acronym for his mantra “T.H.U.G. L.I.F.E.”: “The hate you gave little infants [expletive] everybody,” he said of systematic injustices. “What you feed us as seeds, grows and blows up in your face.” More than two decades after his death, his message was worked into “The Hate U Give,” Angie Thomas’s best-selling 2017 novel about a black teenager who experiences those inequalities firsthand.

headline.main: Review: In ‘The Hate U Give,’ a Police Shooting Forces a Teen to Find Her Voice

docs.lead_paragraph: AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. — In Washington, Republicans were dealing with a burgeoning crisis in their ranks, with high-profile resignations and bitter infighting over how to deal with an erratic and isolated president. But at the Republican National Committee’s winter meeting on Friday, most party members were operating in a parallel universe.

headline.main: In Capital, a G.O.P. Crisis. At the R.N.C. Meeting, a Trump Celebration.
